---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is included in a monthly mortgage payment?",
    a: "A standard monthly mortgage payment includes four main components, often abbreviated as PITI: Principal (paying down the loan balance), Interest (the cost of borrowing), Taxes (local property taxes), and Insurance (homeowner's insurance). If your down payment is less than 20%, it may also include PMI (Private Mortgage Insurance)."
  },
  {
    q: "How much house can I afford?",
    a: "A common rule of thumb is the 28/36 rule: your housing costs should not exceed 28% of your gross monthly income, and your total debt payments (including the mortgage) should not exceed 36%. You can use our Affordability Calculator to get a personalized estimate based on your income and debts."
  },
  {
    q: "What is PMI and how can I avoid it?",
    a: "PMI stands for Private Mortgage Insurance. Lenders usually require it if your down payment is less than 20% of the home's purchase price. It protects the lender in case you default. To avoid PMI, you need to put down at least 20%, or you can ask to have it removed once you've built up 20% equity in your home."
  },
  {
    q: "Should I choose a 15-year or 30-year mortgage?",
    a: "A 30-year mortgage offers lower monthly payments, which can make it easier to qualify and afford your day-to-day expenses. However, you will pay significantly more in total interest over the life of the loan. A 15-year mortgage has higher monthly payments but typically comes with a lower interest rate, saving you tens or hundreds of thousands of dollars in interest."
  },
  {
    q: "How do property taxes impact my mortgage?",
    a: "Property taxes are collected by your local government and vary widely depending on where you live. Lenders typically divide your annual property tax bill by 12 and add that amount to your monthly mortgage payment, holding it in an escrow account until the tax bill is due. High property taxes can significantly increase your monthly payment."
  },
  {
    q: "When is the right time to refinance?",
    a: "It's generally a good idea to consider refinancing if you can lower your interest rate by at least 0.75% to 1%, if your credit score has improved significantly, or if you want to switch from an adjustable-rate to a fixed-rate mortgage. You should also calculate the 'break-even' point to ensure the monthly savings outweigh the closing costs of the new loan."
  },
  {
    q: "What credit score do I need to buy a house?",
    a: "The minimum credit score depends on the loan type. Conventional loans typically require a minimum score of 620. FHA loans are more lenient, allowing scores as low as 580 for a 3.5% down payment. VA loans don't have a strict government-mandated minimum, but most lenders look for a score around 620. Jumbo loans generally require scores of 700 or higher."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a down payment?",
    a: "A down payment is the upfront cash you pay toward the purchase price of a home. It is expressed as a percentage of the total price. For example, a 20% down payment on a $300,000 home is $60,000. The remaining amount is financed through your mortgage."
  },
  {
    q: "Do I have to put 20% down?",
    a: "No, you do not need a 20% down payment to buy a house. Many first-time homebuyer programs and conventional loans allow down payments as low as 3%. FHA loans require just 3.5%, and VA or USDA loans often require zero down. However, putting down less than 20% usually means you will have to pay for mortgage insurance."
  },
  {
    q: "What are closing costs?",
    a: "Closing costs are the fees and expenses you pay to finalize your mortgage. They typically include appraisal fees, title insurance, loan origination fees, attorney fees, and prepaid taxes and insurance. Closing costs usually range from 2% to 5% of the total loan amount."
  },
  {
    q: "What is the difference between a fixed-rate and an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM)?",
    a: "A fixed-rate mortgage keeps the exact same interest rate and principal/interest payment for the entire life of the loan (e.g., 30 years). An adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) has a fixed rate for an initial period (e.g., 5 or 7 years), after which the rate adjusts periodically based on the market, which means your payment can go up or down."
  },
  {
    q: "What does it mean to be pre-approved for a mortgage?",
    a: "A pre-approval is a letter from a lender stating that they are willing to lend you a specific amount of money based on a thorough review of your credit, income, and assets. Being pre-approved shows sellers that you are a serious and qualified buyer, which gives you an advantage when making an offer."
  },
  {
    q: "What is an escrow account?",
    a: "An escrow account is a specialized holding account managed by your lender. A portion of your monthly mortgage payment goes into this account to cover your annual property taxes and homeowner's insurance premiums. When those bills are due, the lender pays them on your behalf using the funds in the escrow account."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a Jumbo loan?",
    a: "A jumbo loan is a mortgage that exceeds the conforming loan limits set by the Federal Housing Finance Agency (FHFA). These limits change annually and vary by county. Because they cannot be guaranteed by Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac, jumbo loans carry more risk for lenders and usually require higher credit scores and larger down payments."
  },
  {
    q: "What is an FHA loan?",
    a: "An FHA loan is a mortgage insured by the Federal Housing Administration. It is popular among first-time homebuyers because it requires a lower minimum down payment (3.5%) and lower credit scores (580) than conventional loans. However, FHA loans require you to pay both an upfront mortgage insurance premium and annual mortgage insurance."
  },
  {
    q: "What is a VA loan?",
    a: "A VA loan is a mortgage backed by the Department of Veterans Affairs, available exclusively to eligible veterans, active-duty service members, and certain surviving spouses. VA loans offer significant benefits, including zero down payment requirements, no private mortgage insurance (PMI), and competitive interest rates."
  },
  {
    q: "What happens if I make extra payments on my mortgage?",
    a: "Making extra payments toward your loan's principal reduces your outstanding balance faster. This means you will pay less total interest over the life of the loan and you will pay off your mortgage sooner. You can use our Extra Payments Calculator to see exactly how much time and money you can save."
  },
  {
    q: "What is an amortization schedule?",
    a: "An amortization schedule is a complete table of periodic loan payments showing the amount of principal and the amount of interest that comprise each payment until the loan is paid off at the end of its term. Early in the loan, most of your payment goes toward interest, but over time, more of it goes toward the principal balance."
  }
];

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": faqs.map(faq => ({
    "@type": "Question",
    "name": faq.q,
    "acceptedAnswer": {
      "@type": "Answer",
      "text": faq.a
    }
  }))
};
import { getLiveRates } from '../utils/rates';
const ratesData = await getLiveRates(Astro);
---

<BaseLayout
  keywords="mortgage faq, mortgage questions, mortgage calculator help, common mortgage questions, mortgage calculator, home loan calculator, current mortgage rates, monthly mortgage payment, free mortgage calculator, mortgage payment calculator, house payment calculator, home mortgage calculator, calculate mortgage, mortgage estimator, monthly house payment, mortgage interest calculator, loan payment calculator, how much is my mortgage, mortgage calculator with taxes, mortgage calculator with PMI, mortgage calculator with insurance, PITI calculator, home buying calculator, home affordability calculator, mortgage amortization, what will my mortgage payment be, mortgage calculator 2025, best mortgage calculator, accurate mortgage calculator, simple mortgage calculator, mortgage calculator USA, home loan payment estimator, mortgage rate calculator, mortgage cost calculator"
  canonicalUrl="/faq/"
  title="Frequently Asked Questions"
  description="Common questions about mortgages, interest rates, down payments, and how to use our mortgage calculator."
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />

  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 pt-16 pb-24">
    <div class="text-center mb-12">
      <h1 class="text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-bold tracking-tight mb-4" style="color: var(--text-primary);">
        Frequently Asked
        <span class="bg-gradient-to-r from-[#06b6d4] to-[#10b981] bg-clip-text text-transparent">Questions</span>
      </h1>
      <p class="text-lg" style="color: var(--text-muted);">
        Everything you need to know about mortgages, rates, and the home-buying process.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      {faqs.map((faq) => (
        <div class="card p-6">
          <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-3" style="color: var(--text-primary);">{faq.q}</h3>
          <p style="color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.6;">{faq.a}</p>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
